{{Infobox philosopher | region = [[Western philosophy]] | school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy]] | era = [[20th-century philosophy]] and [[contemporary philosophy]] | color = #B0C4DE | image = Svob 01.jpeg | caption = Švob while lecturing in 2008 | name = Goran Švob | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1947|05|29}} | birth_place = [[Zagreb]], [[SR Croatia]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2013|04|18|1947|05|29}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://upf.hr/novosti/91-svob.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130822151537/http://upf.hr/novosti/91-svob.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2013-08-22 |title=In memoriam - Goran Švob |publisher=Upf.hr |date= |accessdate=2013-08-22 }}</ref> | influences = [[Gottlob Frege]]{{·}}[[Bertrand Russell]]{{·}}[[Ludwig Wittgenstein]] | main_interests = [[Logic]]{{·}}[[Philosophy of language]]{{·}}[[Ordinary language philosophy]]{{·}}[[Logical positivism]] | website = [http://www-wpt.ffzg.hr/filoz/nastavnici/goran-svob/ Biography]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} }}
'''Goran Švob''' ({{IPA-sh|ɡoran ʃʋob|pron}}; 29 May 1947 – 18 April 2013) was a Croatian [[Philosophy|philosopher]], [[logic]]ian, and author. He was an associate professor at the Department of Philosophy of [[University of Zagreb Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences|Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences]], [[University of Zagreb]] where he taught logic and the [[philosophy of language]], being employed there since 1975.
Švob has written two books and published numerous scientific papers in the academic field of [[logic]]. He was greatly influenced by the [[analytic philosophy]] and particularly by the philosophers [[Gottlob Frege]], [[Bertrand Russell]], and [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]].
==Education and academic career== Švob was born on 29 May 1947 in [[Zagreb]], then part of [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]. There he finished his primary school education and graduated from [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]]. He then enrolled at the [[University of Zagreb Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences|Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences]] of the [[University of Zagreb]] where he got his [[Master of Arts]] in [[philosophy]] and [[English language]] in 1971. The same year he managed to get employed at the Department of Philosophy of the same faculty.
During the academic year 1973–1974 Švob spent six months as a research fellow at the [[University of Oxford]]. He also had shorter visits at the universities in [[Austria]], [[West Germany]], [[Great Britain]], [[Japan]], and [[China]]. In 1988 he got his [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in philosophy at the Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences, and the following year he was selected to the position of an assistant professor, and was further promoted to the position of associate professor in 2001. He has been teaching logic and philosophy of language there since 1975. He was also a guest lecturer at the [[University of Vienna]], [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich]], [[Peking University]], [[Hokkaido University]], [[University of Tokyo]], and [[Kyoto University]].
Švob was the leader of scientific research project ''Logic, Universal Language and the Philosophy of Language'' ([[Croatian language|Croatian]]: ''Logika, univerzalni jezik i filozofija jezika'') of the [[Ministry of Science, Education and Sports (Croatia)|Ministry of Science, Education and Sports of the Republic of Croatia]].<ref name=biografija/>
==Published work== Švob published scientific papers in leading philosophical journals, in particular the journal of [[Praxis School]], ''Filozofska istraživanja'', ''SOL'', and, most notably, ''Acta Analytica''. His first book, titled ''Frege: Pojmovno pismo'' (English: ''Frege: Conceptual Notation''), was published in 1992.<ref name=biografija/>
''Od slike do igre'' (English: ''From Image to Game'') was a second book written by Švob, published in 2009. The book is consolidated of articles which differ by subject and time when they were written, though they all mainly focus on the work of three philosophers: [[Gottlob Frege]], [[Bertrand Russell]], and [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]]. The focal point of the book, however, is the shift in Wittgenstein's philosophy of language, or the transition from the early to late Wittgenstein.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profil.hr/knjiga/od-slike-do-igre/31426/ |title=Goran Švob: Od slike do igre |accessdate=18 December 2011 |publisher=Profil.hr |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605144850/http://www.profil.hr/knjiga/od-slike-do-igre/31426/ |archivedate=5 June 2012 |df= }}</ref>
