{{Eastern Orthodox sidebar}}
[[Protopresbyter]] (Very Rev.) Fr. '''Nikolaos Loudovikos''' ({{lang-el|π. Νικόλαος Λουδοβίκος}}) is a [[Greek people|Greek]] [[theologian]], [[priest]], [[psychologist]], [[author]] and [[professor]].

==Biography==
Fr. Nikolaos Loudovikos was born in [[Volos]], [[Greece]] in 1959. He studied Psychology and Education at the [[University of Athens]], Theology at the [[University of Thessaloniki]], [[Philosophy]] at the [[University of Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]], Philosophy and [[Roman Catholic]] Theology at the [[Catholic Institute of Paris]], Philosophy and [[Protestant]] Theology at the [[University of Cambridge]] (England).<ref>{{cite web | title= Father Nicolaos Loudovicos | publisher=Cosmos in Science and Religion - Under the Auspices of  Aristotle University of Thessaloniki  | url=http://diacentro.physics.auth.gr/eng/cv/cv_eng_loudovicos.html | accessdate= 2009-02-22 }}</ref> He received a Ph.D in 1989 from the Theological faculty of Aristotle University of Thessaloniki. The title of his dissertation was: ''The Eucharistic Ontology in the Theological Thought of [[St. Maximus the Confessor]]''.<ref>{{cite web | title=Hē eucharistiakē ontologia stēn theologikē skepsē tou Hag. Maximou tou Homologētē by Nikolaos Loudovikos |url=http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/80156483?&lang=en | publisher=WorldCat | accessdate=2009-02-22}}</ref> 

He has worked as a researcher at the [[Tyndale House (Cambridge)]] and has taught and lectured at the Centre for Advanced Religious and Theological Studies  (CARTS) of the Department of Theology at the University of Cambridge, at [[Durham University]], as well as at other Universities and Research Centres. Today he is the Chair of the Department of Theology and Pastoral Studies and a Professor of Dogmatics and Philosophy at the University Ecclesiastical Academy of Thessaloniki, a Visiting Professor at the Institute for Orthodox Christian Studies in Cambridge, and an Honorary Research Fellow at the University of Winchester, U.K.<ref>{{cite web | title=Theology - Nikolaos Loudovikos (in Greek) | last=Vavavalis | first=Pavlos | accessdate=2009-02-22 |url=http://www.romios.bravehost.com/theologia/loudobikos.html }}</ref> 

Fr. Nikolaos Loudovikos is member and co-secretary (Orthodox) of the ''Saint Irenaeus Joint Orthodox-Catholic Working Group''.<ref>{{cite web | title=Saint Irenaeus Working Group | publisher=Johann-Adam-Moehler-Institute for Ecumenics, Paderborn | accessdate=2009-02-22 | url=http://www.moehlerinstitut.de/sites/eng/03curre/03akie.html}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

==Quotes==
"Fortunately, [[Christianity]] is neither [[Platonism]] nor [[Stoicism]]. Everything in our body and soul is created by God, and as such, absolutely sacred. It is up to my own freedom to get angry, fall in love, play, create, eat, rejoice, be sorrowful, in such a manner that will bring me continuously closer to the Divine Source of my being: this is the meaning of the [[Incarnation]]. God does not call me to escape from this world, but to transform it into a place of His manifestation"<ref>{{cite news | title=We put phantasies about Power and Dominion in the Place of God - Georgios Kiousis interviews Father Nikolaos Loudovikos | publisher=Eleftherotypia | date=2008-04-23 |  accessdate=2009-02-22 | language=Greek | last=Kiousis | first=Georgios |url=http://www.enet.gr/online/online_text/c=112,dt=23.04.2008,id=95738224  }}</ref>

"[[Anselm of Canterbury|Anselm]] says: why did the Incarnation happen? So that the [[Son of God]] could be punished in the place of man. [[Gregory the Theologian]] says: the Incarnation happened, 'because humanity must be sanctified by the Humanity of God'. Quite the opposite, in other words. And the Theologian continues: the only thing God wants, is to stop decay. Now try and build [[Legalism (theology)|legalism]] on a position such as that of the [[Greek Fathers]]! It is impossible. That's why many of my fellow students in France marvelled at us Greeks, saying: «vous êtes anarchistes» (you are anarchists)!"<ref>{{cite news | title=Let's not Lose the Passions. Let's Transform them - Apostolos Diamantis interviews Father Nikolaos Loudovikos | publisher=Anti  | date=2007-01-13 | language=Greek | last=Diamantis | first=Apostolos | url=http://www.europeanspirit.gr/athenaeum/nikolaos_pathi.html |  accessdate=2009-02-22 }}</ref>

